cells of the immune system to grow and has been thought to
bolster the body's immunity. In addition to interleukin-1, a
related substance, interleukin-2, has undergone testing at
the National Cancer Institute. It is a possible anti-cancer
drug that also strengthens the immune system. Cistron said it
believes the material has potential uses in the treatment of
cancer and such autoimmune diseases as arthritis and systemic
lupus.
